[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] The **exponential mechanism** is a technique for designing differentially private algorithms.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] It was developed by Frank McSherry and Kunal Talwar in 2007.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Their work was recognized as a co-winner of the 2009 PET Award for Outstanding Research in Privacy Enhancing Technologies.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Most of the initial research in the field of differential privacy revolved around real-valued functions which have relatively low sensitivity to change in the data of a single individual and whose usefulness is not hampered by small additive perturbations.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] A natural question is what happens in the situation when one wants to preserve more general sets of properties.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] The exponential mechanism helps to extend the notion of differential privacy to address these issues.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Moreover, it describes a class of mechanisms that includes all possible differentially private mechanisms.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] In very generic terms, a privacy mechanism maps a set of $n\,\!$ inputs from domain ${\mathcal {D}}\,\!$ to a range ${\mathcal {R}}\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] The map may be randomized, in which case each element of the domain ${\mathcal {D}}\,\!$ corresponds to a probability distribution over the range ${\mathcal {R}}\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] The privacy mechanism makes no assumption about the nature of ${\mathcal {D}}\,\!$ and ${\mathcal {R}}\,\!$ apart from a base measure $\mu \,\!$ on ${\mathcal {R}}\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Let us define a function $q:{\mathcal {D}}^{n}\times {\mathcal {R}}\rightarrow \mathbb {R} \,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] The score reflects the appeal of the pair $(d,r)\,\!$ , i.e. the higher the score, the more appealing the pair is.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Given the input $d\in {\mathcal {D}}^{n}\,\!$ , the mechanism's objective is to return an $r\in {\mathcal {R}}\,\!$ such that the function $q(d,r)\,\!$ is approximately maximized.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] This definition implies the fact that the probability of returning an $r\,\!$ increases exponentially with the increase in the value of $q(d,r)\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Ignoring the base measure $\mu \,\!$ then the value $r\,\!$ which maximizes $q(d,r)\,\!$ has the highest probability.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Moreover, this mechanism is differentially private.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] One technicality that should be kept in mind is that in order to properly define ${\mathcal {E}}_{q}^{\varepsilon }(d)\,\!$ the $\int _{r}e^{\varepsilon q(d,r)}\times \mu (r)\,\!$ should be finite.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Now, if a single change in $d\,\!$ changes $q\,\!$ by at most $\Delta q\,\!$ then the numerator can change at most by a factor of $e^{\varepsilon \Delta q}\,\!$ and the denominator minimum by a factor of $e^{-\varepsilon \Delta q}\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Thus, the ratio of the new probability density (i.e. with new $d\,\!$ ) and the earlier one is at most $\exp(2\varepsilon \Delta q)\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] We would ideally want the random draws of $r\,\!$ from the mechanism ${\mathcal {E}}_{q}^{\varepsilon }(d)\,\!$ to nearly maximize $q(d,r)\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] If we consider $\max _{r}q(d,r)\,\!$ to be $OPT\,\!$ then we can show that the probability of the mechanism deviating from $OPT\,\!$ is low, as long as there is a sufficient mass (in terms of $\mu$ ) of values $r\,\!$ with value $q\,\!$ close to the optimum.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] The value of $\mu ({\bar {S}}_{2t})\,\!$ is at most one, and so this bound implies the lemma statement.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Proof: It follows from the previous lemma that the probability of the score being at least $OPT-2t\,\!$ is $1-\exp(-\varepsilon t)/\mu (S_{t})\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Substituting the value of $t\,\!$ we get this probability to be at least $1-t/OPT\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Multiplying with $OPT-2t\,\!$ yields the desired bound.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] We can assume $\mu (A)\,\!$ for $A\subseteq {\mathcal {R}}\,\!$ to be less than or equal to one in all the computations, because we can always normalize with $\mu ({\mathcal {R}})\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Before we get into the details of the example let us define some terms which we will be using extensively throughout our discussion.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] The following is due to Avrim Blum, Katrina Ligett and Aaron Roth.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Informally, it means that with high probability the query $Q_{h}\,\!$ will behave in a similar way on the original dataset $D\,\!$ and on the synthetic dataset ${\widehat {D}}\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Consider a common problem in Data Mining.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Assume there is a database $D\,\!$ with $n\,\!$ entries.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] In essence the user wants to figure out the values of $\pi _{1},\pi _{2},\dots ,\pi _{k-1}\,\!$ such that maximum number of tuples in the database satisfy the inequality.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] The algorithm we describe below can generate a synthetic database ${\widehat {D}}\,\!$ which will allow the user to learn (approximately) the same linear half-space while querying on this synthetic database.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] The motivation for such an algorithm being that the new database will be generated in a differentially private manner and thus assure privacy to the individual records in the database $D\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] we can output an $(\alpha ,\delta )\,\!$ -useful dataset ${\widehat {D}}\,\!$ that preserves $\varepsilon \,\!$ -differential privacy.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] As we had mentioned earlier the algorithm need not be efficient.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] One interesting fact is that the algorithm which we are going to develop generates a synthetic dataset whose size is independent of the original dataset; in fact, it only depends on the VC-dimension of the concept class and the parameter $\alpha \,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] We borrow the Uniform Convergence Theorem from combinatorics and state a corollary of it which aligns to our need.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] where probability is over the distribution of the dataset.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Thus, if the RHS is less than one then we know for sure that the data set ${\widehat {D}}\,\!$ exists.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] To bound the RHS to less than one we need $m\geq \lambda (\operatorname {VCDim} (H)\log(m/\operatorname {VCDim} (H))/\alpha ^{2})\,\!$ , where $\lambda \,\!$ is some positive constant.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Since we stated earlier that we will output a dataset of size ${\tilde {O}}(\operatorname {VCDim} (H)/\alpha ^{2})\,\!$ , so using this bound on $m\,\!$ we get $m\geq \lambda (\operatorname {VCDim} (H)\log(1/\alpha )/\alpha ^{2})\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Now we invoke the exponential mechanism.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] From the exponential mechanism we know this preserves $(\varepsilon nGS_{q})\,\!$ -differential privacy.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Let's get back to the proof of the Theorem.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] To show that the mechanism satisfies the $(\alpha ,\delta )\,\!$ -usefulness, we should show that it outputs some dataset ${\widehat {D}}\,\!$ with $q(D,{\widehat {D}})\geq -\alpha \,\!$ with probability $1-\delta \,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] There are at most $2^{km}\,\!$ output datasets and the probability that $q(D,{\widehat {D}})\leq -\alpha \,\!$ is at most proportional to $e^{-\varepsilon \alpha n/2}\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Thus by union bound, the probability of outputting any such dataset ${\widehat {D}}\,\!$ is at most proportional to $2^{km}e^{-\varepsilon \alpha n/2}\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Therefore, such a dataset is output with probability at least proportional to $e^{-\alpha \varepsilon n/4}\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Let $A:=\,\!$ the event that the exponential mechanism outputs some dataset ${\widehat {D}}\,\!$ such that $q(D,{\widehat {D}})\geq -\alpha /2\,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] $B:=\,\!$ the event that the exponential mechanism outputs some dataset ${\widehat {D}}\,\!$ such that $q(D,{\widehat {D}})\leq -\alpha \,\!$ .
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] In the above example of the usage of exponential mechanism, one can output a synthetic dataset in a differentially private manner and can use the dataset to answer queries with good accuracy.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Other private mechanisms, such as posterior sampling, which returns parameters rather than datasets, can be made equivalent to the exponential one.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] Apart from the setting of privacy, the exponential mechanism has also been studied in the context of auction theory and classification algorithms.
[src:regret-minimization/exponential-mechanism] In the case of auctions the exponential mechanism helps to achieve a *truthful* auction setting.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] More generally, it is a problem in which a decision maker iteratively selects one of multiple fixed choices (i.e., arms or actions) when the properties of each choice are only partially known at the time of allocation, and may become better understood as time passes.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A fundamental aspect of bandit problems is that choosing an arm does not affect the properties of the arm or other arms.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Instances of the multi-armed bandit problem include the task of iteratively allocating a fixed, limited set of resources between competing (alternative) choices in a way that minimizes the regret.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A notable alternative setup for the multi-armed bandit problem includes the "**best arm identification (BAI)**" problem where the goal is instead to identify the best choice by the end of a finite number of rounds.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The multi-armed bandit problem is a classic reinforcement learning problem that exemplifies the exploration–exploitation tradeoff dilemma.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In contrast to general reinforcement learning, the selected actions in bandit problems do not affect the reward distribution of the arms.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The multi-armed bandit problem also falls into the broad category of stochastic scheduling.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In the problem, each machine provides a random reward from a probability distribution specific to that machine, that is not known *a priori*.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The objective of the gambler is to maximize the sum of rewards earned through a sequence of lever pulls.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The crucial tradeoff the gambler faces at each trial is between "exploitation" of the machine that has the highest expected payoff and "exploration" to get more information about the expected payoffs of the other machines.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The trade-off between exploration and exploitation is also faced in machine learning.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In practice, multi-armed bandits have been used to model problems such as managing research projects in a large organization, like a science foundation or a pharmaceutical company.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In early versions of the problem, the gambler begins with no initial knowledge about the machines.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Herbert Robbins in 1952, realizing the importance of the problem, constructed convergent population selection strategies in "some aspects of the sequential design of experiments".
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A theorem, the Gittins index, first published by John C.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Gittins, gives an optimal policy for maximizing the expected discounted reward.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The multi-armed bandit problem models an agent that simultaneously attempts to acquire new knowledge (called "exploration") and optimize their decisions based on existing knowledge (called "exploitation").
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The agent attempts to balance these competing tasks in order to maximize their total value over the period of time considered.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In these practical examples, the problem requires balancing reward maximization based on the knowledge already acquired with attempting new actions to further increase knowledge.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] This is known as the *exploitation vs. exploration tradeoff* in machine learning.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The model has also been used to control dynamic allocation of resources to different projects, answering the question of which project to work on, given uncertainty about the difficulty and payoff of each possibility.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Originally considered by Allied scientists in World War II, it proved so intractable that, according to Peter Whittle, the problem was proposed to be dropped over Germany so that German scientists could also waste their time on it.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The version of the problem now commonly analyzed was formulated by Herbert Robbins in 1952.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The multi-armed bandit (short: *bandit* or MAB) can be seen as a set of real distributions $B=\{R_{1},\dots ,R_{K}\}$ , each distribution being associated with the rewards delivered by one of the $K\in \mathbb {N} ^{+}$ levers.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Let $\mu _{1},\dots ,\mu _{K}$ be the mean values associated with these reward distributions.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The gambler iteratively plays one lever per round and observes the associated reward.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The objective is to maximize the sum of the collected rewards.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The horizon H is the number of rounds that remain to be played.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The bandit problem is formally equivalent to a one-state Markov decision process.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A *zero-regret strategy* is a strategy whose average regret per round $\rho /T$ tends to zero with probability 1 when the number of played rounds tends to infinity.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Intuitively, zero-regret strategies are guaranteed to converge to a (not necessarily unique) optimal strategy if enough rounds are played.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A common formulation is the *Binary multi-armed bandit* or *Bernoulli multi-armed bandit,* which issues a reward of one with probability p , and otherwise a reward of zero.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Another formulation of the multi-armed bandit has each arm representing an independent Markov machine.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Each time a particular arm is played, the state of that machine advances to a new one, chosen according to the Markov state evolution probabilities.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] There is a reward depending on the current state of the machine.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In a generalization called the "restless bandit problem", the states of non-played arms can also evolve over time.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] There has also been discussion of systems where the number of choices (about which arm to play) increases over time.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Computer science researchers have studied multi-armed bandits under worst-case assumptions, obtaining algorithms to minimize regret in both finite and infinite (asymptotic) time horizons for both stochastic and non-stochastic arm payoffs.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] An important variation of the classical *regret minimization* problem in multi-armed bandits is best arm identification (BAI), also known as *pure exploration*.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] This problem is crucial in various applications, including clinical trials, adaptive routing, recommendation systems, and A/B testing.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In BAI, the objective is to identify the arm having the highest expected reward.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] From there you get your results either positive or negative to add for N with your own specific rule) and i as the maximum you are willing to spend.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] It is possible to express this construction using a combination of multiple algebraic formulation, as mentioned above where you can limit with T for, or in time and so on.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A major breakthrough was the construction of optimal population selection strategies, or policies (that possess uniformly maximum convergence rate to the population with highest mean) in the work described below.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Then, in Katehakis and Robbins simplifications of the policy and the main proof were given for the case of normal populations with known variances.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Burnetas and Katehakis (1996) also provided an explicit solution for the important case in which the distributions of outcomes follow arbitrary (i.e., non-parametric) discrete, univariate distributions.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Later in "Optimal adaptive policies for Markov decision processes" Burnetas and Katehakis studied the much larger model of Markov Decision Processes under partial information, where the transition law and/or the expected one period rewards may depend on unknown parameters.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In this work, the authors constructed an explicit form for a class of adaptive policies with uniformly maximum convergence rate properties for the total expected finite horizon reward under sufficient assumptions of finite state-action spaces and irreducibility of the transition law.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A main feature of these policies is that the choice of actions, at each state and time period, is based on indices that are inflations of the right-hand side of the estimated average reward optimality equations.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] These inflations have recently been called the optimistic approach in the work of Tewari and Bartlett, Ortner Filippi, Cappé, and Garivier, and Honda and Takemura.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Pilarski et al. later extended this work in "Delayed Reward Bernoulli Bandits: Optimal Policy and Predictive Meta-Algorithm PARDI" to create a method of determining the optimal policy for Bernoulli bandits when rewards may not be immediately revealed following a decision and may be delayed.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] This method relies upon calculating expected values of reward outcomes which have not yet been revealed and updating posterior probabilities when rewards are revealed.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] When optimal solutions to multi-arm bandit tasks are used to derive the value of animals' choices, the activity of neurons in the amygdala and ventral striatum encodes the values derived from these policies, and can be used to decode when the animals make exploratory versus exploitative choices.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Moreover, optimal policies better predict animals' choice behavior than alternative strategies (described below).
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] This suggests that the optimal solutions to multi-arm bandit problems are biologically plausible, despite being computationally demanding.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Many strategies exist which provide an approximate solution to the bandit problem, and can be put into the four broad categories detailed below.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Semi-uniform strategies were the earliest (and simplest) strategies discovered to approximately solve the bandit problem.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] All those strategies have in common a greedy behavior where the *best* lever (based on previous observations) is always pulled except when a (uniformly) random action is taken.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Probability matching strategies reflect the idea that the number of pulls for a given lever should *match* its actual probability of being the optimal lever.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Probability matching strategies are also known as Thompson sampling or Bayesian Bandits, and are surprisingly easy to implement if you can sample from the posterior for the mean value of each alternative.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Probability matching strategies also admit solutions to so-called contextual bandit problems.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Pricing strategies establish a *price* for each lever.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] For example, as illustrated with the POKER algorithm, the price can be the sum of the expected reward plus an estimation of extra future rewards that will gain through the additional knowledge.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The lever of highest price is always pulled.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A useful generalization of the multi-armed bandit is the contextual multi-armed bandit.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] At each iteration an agent still has to choose between arms, but they also see a d-dimensional feature vector, the context vector they can use together with the rewards of the arms played in the past to make the choice of the arm to play.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Over time, the learner's aim is to collect enough information about how the context vectors and rewards relate to each other, so that it can predict the next best arm to play by looking at the feature vectors.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Many strategies exist that provide an approximate solution to the contextual bandit problem, and can be put into two broad categories detailed below.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In practice, there is usually a cost associated with the resource consumed by each action and the total cost is limited by a budget in many applications such as crowdsourcing and clinical trials.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Constrained contextual bandit (CCB) is such a model that considers both the time and budget constraints in a multi-armed bandit setting.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Badanidiyuru et al. first studied contextual bandits with budget constraints, also referred to as Resourceful Contextual Bandits, and show that a $O({\sqrt {T}})$ regret is achievable.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] However, their work focuses on a finite set of policies, and the algorithm is computationally inefficient.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Another variant of the multi-armed bandit problem is called the adversarial bandit, first introduced by Auer and Cesa-Bianchi (1998).
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In this variant, at each iteration, an agent chooses an arm and an adversary simultaneously chooses the payoff structure for each arm.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] This is one of the strongest generalizations of the bandit problem as it removes all assumptions of the distribution and a solution to the adversarial bandit problem is a generalized solution to the more specific bandit problems.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] An example often considered for adversarial bandits is the iterated prisoner's dilemma.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In this example, each adversary has two arms to pull.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Standard stochastic bandit algorithms don't work very well with these iterations.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] For example, if the opponent cooperates in the first 100 rounds, defects for the next 200, then cooperates in the following 300, etc. then algorithms such as UCB won't be able to react very quickly to these changes.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] This is because after a certain point sub-optimal arms are rarely pulled to limit exploration and focus on exploitation.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] When the environment changes the algorithm is unable to adapt or may not even detect the change.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] EXP3 is a popular algorithm for adversarial multiarmed bandits, suggested and analyzed in this setting by Auer et al. [2002b].
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The paper presented an empirical evaluation and improved analysis of the performance of the EXP3 algorithm in the stochastic setting, as well as a modification of the EXP3 algorithm capable of achieving "logarithmic" regret in stochastic environment.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Exp3 chooses an arm at random with probability $(1-\gamma )$ it prefers arms with higher weights (exploit), it chooses with probability $\gamma$ to uniformly randomly explore.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] After receiving the rewards the weights are updated.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The exponential growth significantly increases the weight of good arms.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] We follow the arm that we think has the best performance so far adding exponential noise to it to provide exploration.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In the original specification and in the above variants, the bandit problem is specified with a discrete and finite number of arms, often indicated by the variable K .
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In the infinite armed case, introduced by Agrawal (1995), the "arms" are a continuous variable in K dimensions.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] This framework refers to the multi-armed bandit problem in a *non-stationary* setting (i.e., in presence of concept drift).
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In the non-stationary setting, it is assumed that the expected reward for an arm k can change at every time step $t\in {\mathcal {T}}$ : $\mu _{t-1}^{k}\neq \mu _{t}^{k}$ .
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Thus, $\mu _{t}^{k}$ no longer represents the whole sequence of expected (stationary) rewards for arm k .
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A *dynamic oracle* represents the optimal policy to be compared with other policies in the non-stationary setting.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The dynamic oracle optimises the expected reward at each step $t\in {\mathcal {T}}$ by always selecting the best arm, with expected reward of $\mu _{t}^{*}$ .
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Garivier and Moulines derive some of the first results with respect to bandit problems where the underlying model can change during play.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A number of algorithms were presented to deal with this case, including Discounted UCB and Sliding-Window UCB.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A similar approach based on Thompson Sampling algorithm is the f-Discounted-Sliding-Window Thompson Sampling (f-dsw TS) proposed by Cavenaghi et al.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The f-dsw TS algorithm exploits a discount factor on the reward history and an arm-related sliding window to contrast concept drift in non-stationary environments.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Another work by Burtini et al. introduces a weighted least squares Thompson sampling approach (WLS-TS), which proves beneficial in both the known and unknown non-stationary cases.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Many variants of the problem have been proposed in recent years.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The dueling bandit variant was introduced by Yue et al.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] (2012) to model the exploration-versus-exploitation tradeoff for relative feedback.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] In this variant the gambler is allowed to pull two levers at the same time, but they only get a binary feedback telling which lever provided the best reward.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The difficulty of this problem stems from the fact that the gambler has no way of directly observing the reward of their actions.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The earliest algorithms for this problem were InterleaveFiltering and Beat-The-Mean.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The relative feedback of dueling bandits can also lead to voting paradoxes.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] A solution is to take the Condorcet winner as a reference.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] More recently, researchers have generalized algorithms from traditional MAB to dueling bandits: Relative Upper Confidence Bounds (RUCB), Relative EXponential weighing (REX3), Copeland Confidence Bounds (CCB), Relative Minimum Empirical Divergence (RMED), and Double Thompson Sampling (DTS).
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Approaches using multiple bandits that cooperate sharing knowledge in order to better optimize their performance started in 2013 with "A Gang of Bandits", an algorithm relying on a similarity graph between the different bandit problems to share knowledge.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The need of a similarity graph was removed in 2014 by the work on the CLUB algorithm.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Following this work, several other researchers created algorithms to learn multiple models at the same time under bandit feedback.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] For example, COFIBA was introduced by Li and Karatzoglou and Gentile (SIGIR 2016), where the classical collaborative filtering, and content-based filtering methods try to learn a static recommendation model given training data.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] The Combinatorial Multiarmed Bandit (CMAB) problem arises when instead of a single discrete variable to choose from, an agent needs to choose values for a set of variables.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Assuming each variable is discrete, the number of possible choices per iteration is exponential in the number of variables.
[src:regret-minimization/multi-armed-bandit] Several CMAB settings have been studied in the literature, from settings where the variables are binary to more general setting where each variable can take an arbitrary set of values.
[src:regret-minimization/online-optimization] In many situations, present decisions (for example, resource allocation) must be made with incomplete knowledge of the future or distributional assumptions on the future are not reliable.
[src:regret-minimization/online-optimization] In such cases, online optimization can be used, which is different from other approaches such as robust optimization, stochastic optimization and Markov decision processes.
[src:regret-minimization/online-optimization] A problem exemplifying the concepts of online algorithms is the Canadian traveller problem.
[src:regret-minimization/online-optimization] The goal of this problem is to minimize the cost of reaching a target in a weighted graph where some of the edges are unreliable and may have been removed from the graph.
[src:regret-minimization/online-optimization] However, whether an edge has been removed (*failed*) is only revealed to *the traveller* when they reach one of the edge's endpoints.
[src:regret-minimization/online-optimization] The worst case for this problem is simply that all of the unreliable edges fail and the problem reduces to the usual shortest path problem.
[src:regret-minimization/online-optimization] An alternative analysis of the problem can be made with the help of competitive analysis.
[src:regret-minimization/online-optimization] For this method of analysis, the offline algorithm knows in advance which edges will fail and the goal is to minimize the ratio between the online and offline algorithms' performance.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] In decision theory, **regret aversion** (or **anticipated regret**) describes how the human emotional response of regret can influence decision-making under uncertainty.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] When individuals make choices without complete information, they often experience regret if they later discover that a different choice would have produced a better outcome.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] This regret can be quantified as the difference in value between the actual decision made and what would have been the optimal decision in hindsight.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Unlike traditional models that consider regret as merely a post-decision emotional response, the theory of regret aversion proposes that decision-makers actively anticipate potential future regret and incorporate this anticipation into their current decision-making process.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] This anticipation can lead individuals to make choices specifically designed to minimize the possibility of experiencing regret later, even if those choices are not optimal from a purely probabilistic expected-value perspective.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Regret is a powerful negative emotion with significant social and reputational implications, playing a central role in how humans learn from experience and in the psychology of risk aversion.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] The conscious anticipation of regret creates a feedback loop that elevates regret from being simply an emotional reaction—often modeled as mere human behavior—into a key factor in rational choice behavior that can be formally modeled in decision theory.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Regret theory is a model in theoretical economics simultaneously developed in 1982 by Graham Loomes and Robert Sugden, David E.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Regret theory models choice under uncertainty taking into account the effect of anticipated regret.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Subsequently, several other authors improved upon it.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] It incorporates a regret term in the utility function which depends negatively on the realized outcome and positively on the best alternative outcome given the uncertainty resolution.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] This regret term is usually an increasing, continuous and non-negative function subtracted to the traditional utility index.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] These types of preferences always violate transitivity in the traditional sense, although most satisfy a weaker version.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] For independent lotteries and when regret is evaluated over the difference between utilities and then averaged over all combinations of outcomes, the regret can still be transitive but for only specific form of regret functional.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] It is shown that only hyperbolic sine function will maintain this property.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] This form of regret inherits most of desired features, such as holding right preferences in face of first order stochastic dominance, risk averseness for logarithmic utilities and the ability to explain Allais paradox.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Regret aversion is not only a theoretical economics model, but a cognitive bias occurring as a decision has been made to abstain from regretting an alternative decision.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] To better preface, regret aversion can be seen through fear by either commission or omission; the prospect of committing to a failure or omitting an opportunity that we seek to avoid.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Regret, feeling sadness or disappointment over something that has happened, can be rationalized for a certain decision, but can guide preferences and can lead people astray.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] This contributes to the spread of disinformation because things are not seen as one's personal responsibility.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Several experiments over both incentivized and hypothetical choices attest to the magnitude of this effect.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Experiments in first price auctions show that by manipulating the feedback the participants expect to receive, significant differences in the average bids are observed.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] In decisions over lotteries, experiments also provide supporting evidence of anticipated regret.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] As in the case of first price auctions, differences in feedback over the resolution of the uncertainty can cause the possibility of regret and if this is anticipated, it may induce different preferences.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] If the coin is tossed regardless of the chosen alternative, then the alternative payoff will always be known and then there is no choice that will eliminate the possibility of regret.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Anticipated regret tends to be overestimated for both choices and actions over which people perceive themselves to be responsible.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] People are particularly likely to overestimate the regret they will feel when missing a desired outcome by a narrow margin.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] In one study, commuters predicted they would experience greater regret if they missed a train by 1 minute more than missing a train by 5 minutes, for example, but commuters who actually missed their train by 1 or 5 minutes experienced (equal and) lower amounts of regret.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Commuters appeared to overestimate the regret they would feel when missing the train by a narrow margin, because they tended to underestimate the extent to which they would attribute missing the train to external causes (e.g., missing their wallet or spending less time in the shower).
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Besides the traditional setting of choices over lotteries, regret aversion has been proposed as an explanation for the typically observed overbidding in first price auctions, and the disposition effect, among others.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] The minimax regret approach is to minimize the worst-case regret, originally presented by Leonard Savage in 1951.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] The aim of this is to perform as closely as possible to the optimal course.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Since the minimax criterion applied here is to the regret (difference or ratio of the payoffs) rather than to the payoff itself, it is not as pessimistic as the ordinary minimax approach.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] One benefit of minimax (as opposed to expected regret) is that it is independent of the probabilities of the various outcomes: thus if regret can be accurately computed, one can reliably use minimax regret.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] However, probabilities of outcomes are hard to estimate.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] This differs from the standard minimax approach in that it uses *differences* or *ratios* between outcomes, and thus requires interval or ratio measurements, as well as ordinal measurements (ranking), as in standard minimax.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Suppose an investor has to choose between investing in stocks, bonds or the money market, and the total return depends on what happens to interest rates.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] The crude maximin choice based on returns would be to invest in the money market, ensuring a return of at least 1.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] However, if interest rates fell then the regret associated with this choice would be large.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] This would be 11, which is the difference between the 12 which could have been received if the outcome had been known in advance and the 1 received.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] A mixed portfolio of about 11.1% in stocks and 88.9% in the money market would have ensured a return of at least 2.22; but, if interest rates fell, there would be a regret of about 9.78.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Therefore, using a minimax choice based on regret, the best course would be to invest in bonds, ensuring a regret of no worse than 5.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] A mixed investment portfolio would do even better: 61.1% invested in stocks, and 38.9% in the money market would produce a regret no worse than about 4.28.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] What follows is an illustration of how the concept of regret can be used to design a linear estimator.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] In this example, the problem is to construct a linear estimator of a finite-dimensional parameter vector x from its noisy linear measurement with known noise covariance structure.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] The loss of reconstruction of x is measured using the mean-squared error (MSE).
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] The unknown parameter vector is known to lie in an ellipsoid E centered at zero.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] The regret is defined to be the difference between the MSE of the linear estimator that doesn't know the parameter x , and the MSE of the linear estimator that knows x .
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Also, since the estimator is restricted to be linear, the zero MSE cannot be achieved in the latter case.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] In this case, the solution of a convex optimization problem gives the optimal, minimax regret-minimizing linear estimator, which can be seen by the following argument.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] where H is a known $n\times m$ matrix with full column rank m , and w is a zero mean random vector with a known covariance matrix $C_{w}$ .
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] be a linear estimate of x from y , where G is some $m\times n$ matrix.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Since the MSE depends explicitly on x it cannot be minimized directly.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Instead, the concept of regret can be used in order to define a linear estimator with good MSE performance.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] This is the smallest MSE achievable with a linear estimate that knows x .
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] In practice this MSE cannot be achieved, but it serves as a bound on the optimal MSE.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] The minimax regret approach here is to minimize the worst-case regret, i.e., $\sup _{x\in E}R(x,G).$ This will allow a performance as close as possible to the best achievable performance in the worst case of the parameter x .
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Although this problem appears difficult, it is an instance of convex optimization and in particular a numerical solution can be efficiently calculated.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Similar ideas can be used when x is random with uncertainty in the covariance matrix.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Camara, Hartline and Johnsen study principal-agent problems.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] These are incomplete-information games between two players called *Principal* and *Agent*, whose payoffs depend on a state of nature known only by the Agent.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] The Principal commits to a policy, then the agent responds, and then the state of nature is revealed.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] They assume that the principal and agent interact repeatedly, and may learn over time from the state history, using reinforcement learning.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] They assume that the agent is driven by regret-aversion.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] In particular, the agent minimizes his *counterfactual internal regret*.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Based on this assumption, they develop mechanisms that minimize the principal's regret.
[src:regret-minimization/regret-decision-theory] Collina, Roth and Shao improve their mechanism both in running-time and in the bounds for regret (as a function of the number of distinct states of nature).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In machine learning and optimal control, **reinforcement learning** (**RL**) is concerned with how an intelligent agent should take actions in a dynamic environment in order to maximize a reward signal.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning is one of the three basic machine learning paradigms, alongside supervised learning and unsupervised learning.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] While supervised learning and unsupervised learning algorithms respectively attempt to discover patterns in labeled and unlabeled data, reinforcement learning involves training an agent through interactions with its environment.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] To learn to maximize rewards from these interactions, the agent makes decisions between trying new actions to learn more about the environment (exploration), or using current knowledge of the environment to take the best action (exploitation).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The search for the optimal balance between these two strategies is known as the exploration–exploitation dilemma.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The environment is typically stated in the form of a Markov decision process, as many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The main difference between classical dynamic programming methods and reinforcement learning algorithms is that the latter do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the Markov decision process, and they target large Markov decision processes where exact methods become infeasible.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Due to its generality, reinforcement learning is studied in many disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimization, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, and statistics.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The purpose of reinforcement learning is for the agent to learn an optimal (or near-optimal) policy that maximizes the reward function or other user-provided reinforcement signal that accumulates from immediate rewards.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This is similar to processes that appear to occur in animal psychology.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] For example, biological brains are hardwired to interpret signals such as pain and hunger as negative reinforcements, and interpret pleasure and food intake as positive reinforcements.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In some circumstances, animals learn to adopt behaviors that optimize these rewards.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This suggests that animals are capable of reinforcement learning.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] A basic reinforcement learning agent interacts with its environment in discrete time steps.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] At each time step t, the agent receives the current state $S_{t}$ and reward $R_{t}$ .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] It then chooses an action $A_{t}$ from the set of available actions, which is subsequently sent to the environment.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The environment moves to a new state $S_{t+1}$ and the reward $R_{t+1}$ associated with the *transition* $(S_{t},A_{t},S_{t+1})$ is determined.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] that maximizes the expected cumulative reward.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Formulating the problem as a Markov decision process assumes the agent directly observes the current environmental state; in this case, the problem is said to have *full observability*.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] If the agent only has access to a subset of states, or if the observed states are corrupted by noise, the agent is said to have *partial observability*, and formally the problem must be formulated as a partially observable Markov decision process.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In both cases, the set of actions available to the agent can be restricted.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] For example, the state of an account balance could be restricted to be positive; if the current value of the state is 3 and the state transition attempts to reduce the value by 4, the transition will not be allowed.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] When the agent's performance is compared to that of an agent that acts optimally, the difference in performance yields the notion of regret.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In order to act near optimally, the agent must reason about long-term consequences of its actions (i.e., maximize future rewards), although the immediate reward associated with this might be negative.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Thus, reinforcement learning is particularly well-suited to problems that include a long-term versus short-term reward trade-off.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] It has been applied successfully to various problems, including energy storage, robot control, photovoltaic generators, backgammon, checkers, Go (AlphaGo), and autonomous driving systems.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Two elements make reinforcement learning powerful: the use of samples to optimize performance, and the use of function approximation to deal with large environments.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The first two of these problems could be considered planning problems (since some form of model is available), while the last one could be considered to be a genuine learning problem.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] However, reinforcement learning converts both planning problems to machine learning problems.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The trade-off between exploration and exploitation has been most thoroughly studied through the multi-armed bandit problem and for finite state space Markov decision processes in Burnetas and Katehakis (1997).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning requires clever exploration mechanisms; randomly selecting actions, without reference to an estimated probability distribution, shows poor performance.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The case of (small) finite Markov decision processes is relatively well understood.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] However, due to the lack of algorithms that scale well with the number of states (or scale to problems with infinite state spaces), simple exploration methods are the most practical.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] One such method is $\varepsilon$ -greedy, where $0<\varepsilon <1$ is a parameter controlling the amount of exploration vs. exploitation.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] With probability $1-\varepsilon$ , exploitation is chosen, and the agent chooses the action that it believes has the best long-term effect (ties between actions are broken uniformly at random).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Alternatively, with probability $\varepsilon$ , exploration is chosen, and the action is chosen uniformly at random. $\varepsilon$ is usually a fixed parameter but can be adjusted either according to a schedule (making the agent explore progressively less), or adaptively based on heuristics.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Even if the issue of exploration is disregarded and even if the state was observable (assumed hereafter), the problem remains to use past experience to find out which actions lead to higher cumulative rewards.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The policy map gives the probability of taking action a when in state s .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] There are also deterministic policies $\pi$ for which $\pi (s)$ denotes the action that should be played at state s .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The state-value function $V_{\pi }(s)$ is defined as, *expected discounted return* starting with state s , i.e. $S_{0}=s$ , and successively following policy $\pi$ .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Hence, roughly speaking, the value function estimates "how good" it is to be in a given state.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] where $R_{t+1}$ is the reward for transitioning from state $S_{t}$ to $S_{t+1}$ , $0\leq \gamma <1$ is the discount rate. $\gamma$ is less than 1, so rewards in the distant future are weighted less than rewards in the immediate future.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The algorithm must find a policy with maximum expected discounted return.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] From the theory of Markov decision processes it is known that, without loss of generality, the search can be restricted to the set of so-called *stationary* policies.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] A policy is *stationary* if the action-distribution returned by it depends only on the last state visited (from the observation agent's history).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The search can be further restricted to *deterministic* stationary policies.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] A *deterministic stationary* policy deterministically selects actions based on the current state.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Since any such policy can be identified with a mapping from the set of states to the set of actions, these policies can be identified with such mappings with no loss of generality.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] One problem with this is that the number of policies can be large, or even infinite.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Another is that the variance of the returns may be large, which requires many samples to accurately estimate the discounted return of each policy.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] These problems can be ameliorated if we assume some structure and allow samples generated from one policy to influence the estimates made for others.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The two main approaches for achieving this are value function estimation and direct policy search.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Value function approaches attempt to find a policy that maximizes the discounted return by maintaining a set of estimates of expected discounted returns $\operatorname {\mathbb {E} } [G]$ for some policy (usually either the "current" [on-policy] or the optimal [off-policy] one).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] These methods rely on the theory of Markov decision processes, where optimality is defined in a sense stronger than the one above: A policy is optimal if it achieves the best-expected discounted return from *any* initial state (i.e., initial distributions play no role in this definition).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Again, an optimal policy can always be found among stationary policies.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] where G stands for the discounted return associated with following $\pi$ from the initial state s .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] A policy that achieves these optimal state-values in each state is called *optimal*.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Clearly, a policy that is optimal in this sense is also optimal in the sense that it maximizes the expected discounted return, since $V^{*}(s)=\max _{\pi }\mathbb {E} [G\mid s,\pi ]$ , where s is a state randomly sampled from the distribution $\mu$ of initial states (so $\mu (s)=\Pr(S_{0}=s)$ ).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Although state-values suffice to define optimality, it is useful to define action-values.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] where G now stands for the random discounted return associated with first taking action a in state s and following $\pi$ , thereafter.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The theory of Markov decision processes states that if $\pi ^{*}$ is an optimal policy, we act optimally (take the optimal action) by choosing the action from $Q^{\pi ^{*}}(s,\cdot )$ with the highest action-value at each state, s .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The *action-value function* of such an optimal policy ( $Q^{\pi ^{*}}$ ) is called the *optimal action-value function* and is commonly denoted by $Q^{*}$ .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In summary, the knowledge of the optimal action-value function alone suffices to know how to act optimally.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Assuming full knowledge of the Markov decision process, the two basic approaches to compute the optimal action-value function are value iteration and policy iteration.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Both algorithms compute a sequence of functions $Q_{k}$ ( $k=0,1,2,\ldots$ ) that converge to $Q^{*}$ .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Computing these functions involves computing expectations over the whole state-space, which is impractical for all but the smallest (finite) Markov decision processes.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In reinforcement learning methods, expectations are approximated by averaging over samples and using function approximation techniques to cope with the need to represent value functions over large state-action spaces.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Monte Carlo methods are used to solve reinforcement learning problems by averaging sample returns.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Unlike methods that require full knowledge of the environment's dynamics, Monte Carlo methods rely solely on actual or simulated experience—sequences of states, actions, and rewards obtained from interaction with an environment.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This makes them applicable in situations where the complete dynamics are unknown.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Learning from actual experience does not require prior knowledge of the environment and can still lead to optimal behavior.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] When using simulated experience, only a model capable of generating sample transitions is required, rather than a full specification of transition probabilities, which is necessary for dynamic programming methods.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Monte Carlo methods apply to episodic tasks, where experience is divided into episodes that eventually terminate.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Policy and value function updates occur only after the completion of an episode, making these methods incremental on an episode-by-episode basis, though not on a step-by-step (online) basis.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The term "Monte Carlo" generally refers to any method involving random sampling; however, in this context, it specifically refers to methods that compute averages from *complete* returns, rather than *partial* returns.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] These methods function similarly to the bandit algorithms, in which returns are averaged for each state-action pair.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The key difference is that actions taken in one state affect the returns of subsequent states within the same episode, making the problem non-stationary.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] To address this non-stationarity, Monte Carlo methods use the framework of general policy iteration (GPI).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] While dynamic programming computes value functions using full knowledge of the Markov decision process, Monte Carlo methods learn these functions through sample returns.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The value functions and policies interact similarly to dynamic programming to achieve optimality, first addressing the prediction problem and then extending to policy improvement and control, all based on sampled experience.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The first problem is corrected by allowing the procedure to change the policy (at some or all states) before the values settle.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This too may be problematic as it might prevent convergence.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Most current algorithms do this, giving rise to the class of *generalized policy iteration* algorithms.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Many *actor-critic* methods belong to this category.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The second issue can be corrected by allowing trajectories to contribute to any state-action pair in them.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This may also help to some extent with the third problem, although a better solution when returns have high variance is Sutton's temporal difference (TD) methods that are based on the recursive Bellman equation.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The computation in TD methods can be incremental (when after each transition the memory is changed and the transition is thrown away), or batch (when the transitions are batched and the estimates are computed once based on the batch).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Batch methods, such as the least-squares temporal difference method, may use the information in the samples better, while incremental methods are the only choice when batch methods are infeasible due to their high computational or memory complexity.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Some methods try to combine the two approaches.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Methods based on temporal differences also overcome the fourth issue.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Another problem specific to TD comes from their reliance on the recursive Bellman equation.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Most TD methods have a so-called $\lambda$ parameter $(0\leq \lambda \leq 1)$ that can continuously interpolate between Monte Carlo methods that do not rely on the Bellman equations and the basic TD methods that rely entirely on the Bellman equations.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This can be effective in palliating this issue.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In order to address the fifth issue, *function approximation methods* are used.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] *Linear function approximation* starts with a mapping $\phi$ that assigns a finite-dimensional vector to each state-action pair.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The algorithms then adjust the weights, instead of adjusting the values associated with the individual state-action pairs.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Methods based on ideas from nonparametric statistics (which can be seen to construct their own features) have been explored.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Value iteration can also be used as a starting point, giving rise to the Q-learning algorithm and its many variants.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Including Deep Q-learning methods when a neural network is used to represent Q, with various applications in stochastic search problems.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The problem with using action-values is that they may need highly precise estimates of the competing action values that can be hard to obtain when the returns are noisy, though this problem is mitigated to some extent by temporal difference methods.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Using the so-called compatible function approximation method compromises generality and efficiency.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] An alternative method is to search directly in (some subset of) the policy space, in which case the problem becomes a case of stochastic optimization.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The two approaches available are gradient-based and gradient-free methods.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Gradient-based methods (*policy gradient methods*) start with a mapping from a finite-dimensional (parameter) space to the space of policies: given the parameter vector $\theta$ , let $\pi _{\theta }$ denote the policy associated to $\theta$ .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Defining the performance function by $\rho (\theta )=\rho ^{\pi _{\theta }}$ under mild conditions this function will be differentiable as a function of the parameter vector $\theta$ .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] If the gradient of $\rho$ was known, one could use gradient ascent.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Since an analytic expression for the gradient is not available, only a noisy estimate is available.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Such an estimate can be constructed in many ways, giving rise to algorithms such as Williams's REINFORCE method (which is known as the likelihood ratio method in the simulation-based optimization literature).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] A large class of methods avoids relying on gradient information.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] These include simulated annealing, cross-entropy search or methods of evolutionary computation.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Many gradient-free methods can achieve (in theory and in the limit) a global optimum.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Policy search methods may converge slowly given noisy data.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] For example, this happens in episodic problems when the trajectories are long and the variance of the returns is large.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Value-function based methods that rely on temporal differences might help in this case.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In recent years, *actor–critic methods* have been proposed and performed well on various problems.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Policy search methods have been used in the robotics context.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Many policy search methods may get stuck in local optima (as they are based on local search).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Finally, all of the above methods can be combined with algorithms that first learn a model of the Markov decision process, the probability of each next state given an action taken from an existing state.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] For instance, the Dyna algorithm learns a model from experience, and uses that to provide more modelled transitions for a value function, in addition to the real transitions.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Such methods can sometimes be extended to use of non-parametric models, such as when the transitions are simply stored and "replayed" to the learning algorithm.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Model-based methods can be more computationally intensive than model-free approaches, and their utility can be limited by the extent to which the Markov decision process can be learnt.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] There are other ways to use models than to update a value function.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] For instance, in model predictive control the model is used to update the behavior directly.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The costly exploration needed to learn an optimal policy can be reduced if some supervised data is available.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This can be achieved for instance by learning a crude control policy and using this to initialize the Q table intelligently instead of with zeros.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Both the asymptotic and finite-sample behaviors of most algorithms are well understood.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Algorithms with provably (i.e. in a way that can be proved) good online performance (addressing the exploration issue) are known.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Efficient exploration of Markov decision processes is given in Burnetas and Katehakis (1997).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Finite-time performance bounds have also appeared for many algorithms, but these bounds are expected to be rather loose and thus more work is needed to better understand the relative advantages and limitations.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] For incremental algorithms, asymptotic convergence issues have been settled.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Temporal-difference-based algorithms converge under a wider set of conditions than was previously possible (for example, when used with arbitrary, smooth function approximation).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Associative reinforcement learning tasks combine facets of stochastic learning automata tasks and supervised learning pattern classification tasks.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In associative reinforcement learning tasks, the learning system interacts in a closed loop with its environment.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This approach extends reinforcement learning by using a deep neural network and without explicitly designing the state space.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The work on learning ATARI games by Google DeepMind increased attention to deep reinforcement learning or end-to-end reinforcement learning.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Adversarial deep reinforcement learning is an active area of research in reinforcement learning focusing on vulnerabilities of learned policies.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In this research area some studies initially showed that reinforcement learning policies are susceptible to imperceptible adversarial manipulations.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] While some methods have been proposed to overcome these susceptibilities, in the most recent studies it has been shown that these proposed solutions are far from providing an accurate representation of current vulnerabilities of deep reinforcement learning policies.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] By introducing fuzzy inference in reinforcement learning, approximating the state-action value function with fuzzy rules in continuous space becomes possible.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The IF - THEN form of fuzzy rules make this approach suitable for expressing the results in a form close to natural language.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Extending FRL with Fuzzy Rule Interpolation allows the use of reduced size sparse fuzzy rule-bases to emphasize cardinal rules (most important state-action values).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In inverse reinforcement learning (IRL), no reward function is given.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Instead, the reward function is inferred given an observed behavior from an expert.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The idea is to mimic observed behavior, which is often optimal or close to optimal.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] One popular IRL paradigm is named maximum entropy inverse reinforcement learning (MaxEnt IRL).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] MaxEnt IRL estimates the parameters of a linear model of the reward function by maximizing the entropy of the probability distribution of observed trajectories subject to constraints related to matching expected feature counts.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Recently it has been shown that MaxEnt IRL is a particular case of a more general framework named random utility inverse reinforcement learning (RU-IRL).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] RU-IRL is based on random utility theory and Markov decision processes.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The utility function is modeled as a random variable to account for the ignorance of the observer regarding the features the observed agent actually considers in its utility function.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Multi-objective reinforcement learning (MORL) is a form of reinforcement learning concerned with conflicting alternatives.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] It is distinct from multi-objective optimization in that it is concerned with agents acting in environments.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Safe reinforcement learning (SRL) can be defined as the process of learning policies that maximize the expectation of the return in problems in which it is important to ensure reasonable system performance and/or respect safety constraints during the learning and/or deployment processes.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] An alternative approach is risk-averse reinforcement learning, where instead of the *expected* return, a *risk-measure* of the return is optimized, such as the conditional value at risk (CVaR).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In addition to mitigating risk, the CVaR objective increases robustness to model uncertainties.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] However, CVaR optimization in risk-averse RL requires special care, to prevent gradient bias and blindness to success.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Self-reinforcement learning (or self-learning), is a learning paradigm which does not use the concept of immediate reward $R_{a}(s,s')$ after transition from s to $s'$ with action a .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] It does not use an external reinforcement, it only uses the agent internal self-reinforcement.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The internal self-reinforcement is provided by mechanism of feelings and emotions.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In the learning process emotions are backpropagated by a mechanism of secondary reinforcement.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The learning equation does not include the immediate reward, it only includes the state evaluation.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Compute state evaluation $v(s')$ of how good it is to be in the consequence situation $s'$ .
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Initial conditions of the memory are received as input from the genetic environment.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] It is a system with only one input (situation), and only one output (action, or behavior).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Self-reinforcement (self-learning) was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-reinforcement learning, named Crossbar Adaptive Array (CAA).
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The CAA computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence states.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Efficient comparison of RL algorithms is essential for research, deployment and monitoring of RL systems.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] To compare different algorithms on a given environment, an agent can be trained for each algorithm.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Since the performance is sensitive to implementation details, all algorithms should be implemented as closely as possible to each other.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] After the training is finished, the agents can be run on a sample of test episodes, and their scores (returns) can be compared.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Since episodes are typically assumed to be i.i.d, standard statistical tools can be used for hypothesis testing, such as T-test and permutation test.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This requires to accumulate all the rewards within an episode into a single number—the episodic return.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] However, this causes a loss of information, as different time-steps are averaged together, possibly with different levels of noise.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Whenever the noise level varies across the episode, the statistical power can be improved significantly, by weighting the rewards according to their estimated noise.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Despite significant advancements, reinforcement learning (RL) continues to face several challenges and limitations that hinder its widespread application in real-world scenarios.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] RL algorithms often require a large number of interactions with the environment to learn effective policies, leading to high computational costs and time-intensive to train the agent.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] For instance, OpenAI's Dota-playing bot utilized thousands of years of simulated gameplay to achieve human-level performance.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Techniques like experience replay and curriculum learning have been proposed to reduce sample inefficiency, but these techniques add more complexity and are not always sufficient for real-world applications.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Training RL models, particularly for deep neural network-based models, can be unstable and prone to divergence.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] A small change in the policy or environment can lead to extreme fluctuations in performance, making it difficult to achieve consistent results.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This instability is further enhanced in the case of the continuous or high-dimensional action space, where the learning step becomes more complex and less predictable.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The RL agents trained in specific environments often struggle to generalize their learned policies to new, unseen scenarios.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This is the major setback preventing the application of RL to dynamic real-world environments where adaptability is crucial.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] The challenge is to develop such algorithms that can transfer knowledge across tasks and environments without extensive retraining.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Designing appropriate reward functions is critical in RL because poorly designed reward functions can lead to unintended behaviors.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In addition, RL systems trained on biased data may perpetuate existing biases and lead to discriminatory or unfair outcomes.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Both of these issues requires careful consideration of reward structures and data sources to ensure fairness and desired behaviors.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] In recent years Since the early 2020s, reinforcement learning has become a significant concept in natural language processing (NLP), where tasks are often sequential decision-making rather than static classification.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning is where an agent take actions in an environment to maximize the accumulation of rewards.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This framework is best fit for many NLP tasks, including dialogue generation, text summarization, and machine translation, where the quality of the output depends on optimizing long-term or human-centered goals rather than the prediction of single correct label.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Early application of RL in NLP emerged in dialogue systems, where conversation was determined as a series of actions optimized for fluency and coherence.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] These early attempts, including policy gradient and sequence-level training techniques, laid a foundation for the broader application of reinforcement learning to other areas of NLP.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] A major breakthrough happened with the introduction of reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), a method in which human feedback ratings are used to train a reward model that guides the RL agent.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] Unlike traditional rule-based or supervised systems, RLHF allows models to align their behavior with human judgments on complex and subjective tasks.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This technique was initially used in the development of InstructGPT, an effective language model trained to follow human instructions and later in ChatGPT which incorporates RLHF for improving output responses and ensuring safety.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] More recently, researchers have explored the use of offline RL in NLP to improve dialogue systems without the need of live human interaction.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] These methods optimize for user engagement, coherence, and diversity based on past conversation logs and pre-trained reward models.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] One example is DeepSeek-R1, which incorporates multi-stage training and cold-start data before RL.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] DeepSeek-R1 achieves performance comparable to OpenAI-o1-1217 on reasoning tasks.
[src:regret-minimization/reinforcement-learning] This model was trained via large-scale RL without supervised fine-tuning (SFT) as a preliminary step.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Consider a set of contexts ${\mathcal {X}}$ , a set of actions ${\mathcal {A}}$ , and rewards in $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] The aim of the player is to play actions under the various contexts, such as to maximize the cumulative rewards.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Specifically, in each round, the player obtains a context $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ , plays an action $a\in {\mathcal {A}}$ and receives a reward $r\in \mathbb {R}$ following a distribution that depends on the context and the issued action.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] 5. a posterior distribution $P(\theta |{\mathcal {D}})\propto P({\mathcal {D}}|\theta )P(\theta )$ , where $P({\mathcal {D}}|\theta )$ is the likelihood function.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] where $\mathbb {I}$ is the indicator function.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] In practice, the rule is implemented by sampling.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] In each round, parameters $\theta ^{\ast }$ are sampled from the posterior $P(\theta |{\mathcal {D}})$ , and an action $a^{\ast }$ chosen that maximizes $\mathbb {E} [r|\theta ^{\ast },a^{\ast },x]$ , i.e. the expected reward given the sampled parameters, the action, and the current context.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Conceptually, this means that the player instantiates their beliefs randomly in each round according to the posterior distribution, and then acts optimally according to them.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] In most practical applications, it is computationally onerous to maintain and sample from a posterior distribution over models.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] As such, Thompson sampling is often used in conjunction with approximate sampling techniques.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Thompson sampling was originally described by Thompson in 1933.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] It was subsequently rediscovered numerous times independently in the context of multi-armed bandit problems.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] A first proof of convergence for the bandit case has been shown in 1997.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] The first application to Markov decision processes was in 2000.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] A related approach (see Bayesian control rule) was published in 2010.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] In 2010 it was also shown that Thompson sampling is *instantaneously self-correcting*.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Asymptotic convergence results for contextual bandits were published in 2011.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Thompson Sampling has been widely used in many online learning problems including A/B testing in website design and online advertising, and accelerated learning in decentralized decision making.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] A Double Thompson Sampling (D-TS) algorithm has been proposed for dueling bandits, a variant of traditional MAB, where feedback comes in the form of pairwise comparison.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Probability matching is a decision strategy in which predictions of class membership are proportional to the class base rates.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] A generalization of Thompson sampling to arbitrary dynamical environments and causal structures, known as **Bayesian control rule**, has been shown to be the optimal solution to the adaptive coding problem with actions and observations.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] In this formulation, an agent is conceptualized as a mixture over a set of behaviours.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] As the agent interacts with its environment, it learns the causal properties and adopts the behaviour that minimizes the relative entropy to the behaviour with the best prediction of the environment's behaviour.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] If these behaviours have been chosen according to the maximum expected utility principle, then the asymptotic behaviour of the Bayesian control rule matches the asymptotic behaviour of the perfectly rational agent.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Let $a_{1},a_{2},\ldots ,a_{T}$ be the actions issued by an agent up to time T , and let $o_{1},o_{2},\ldots ,o_{T}$ be the observations gathered by the agent up to time T .
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] where the "hat"-notation ${\hat {a}}_{t}$ denotes the fact that $a_{t}$ is a causal intervention (see Causality), and not an ordinary observation.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] where $P(\theta |{\hat {a}}_{1:T},o_{1:T})$ is the posterior distribution over the parameter $\theta$ given actions $a_{1:T}$ and observations $o_{1:T}$ .
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Thompson sampling and upper-confidence bound algorithms share a fundamental property that underlies many of their theoretical guarantees.
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Roughly speaking, both algorithms allocate exploratory effort to actions that might be optimal and are in this sense "optimistic".
[src:regret-minimization/thompson-sampling] Leveraging this property, one can translate regret bounds established for UCB algorithms to Bayesian regret bounds for Thompson sampling or unify regret analysis across both these algorithms and many classes of problems.
